  "article": "Labour MP Dawn Butler has called for an 'urgent explanation' from the BBC after a racial slur was heard during the broadcaster's live coverage of the BAFTA awards ceremony.

The incident occurred as the BBC was airing the annual film and television awards show on Sunday evening. During a cutaway shot, a racial epithet could be clearly heard in the background audio.

Butler, the Member of Parliament for Brent Central, immediately took to social media to express her outrage and demand accountability from the BBC. 'I am appalled to hear a racial slur used during the BAFTA's broadcast on the BBC,' she tweeted. 'This is unacceptable. The BBC must now provide an urgent explanation.'

The MP's intervention has thrust the issue into the national spotlight, with many viewers and commentators expressing shock and dismay that such offensive language was broadcast on primetime television. The BBC has not yet issued a public statement addressing the incident, though it is understood that the corporation is investigating how the slur made it onto the live feed.

Critics have accused the BBC of failing to properly vet and monitor its live output, arguing that a racial epithet should never have been audible during a high-profile awards show watched by millions. There are also calls for the corporation to explain how the offensive language was able to be broadcast, and to outline the steps it will take to prevent similar incidents from occurring in the future.

For her part, Butler has been a vocal advocate for racial equality and has frequently spoken out against racism in British society. Her demand for an 'urgent explanation' from the BBC underscores the seriousness with which she views this latest incident, which she has described as 'unacceptable.'

The fallout from the BAFTA broadcast slur is likely to intensify pressure on the BBC to demonstrate that it is taking issues of race and diversity seriously, both in its programming and in its internal practices. With the corporation already facing scrutiny over its handling of high-profile scandals, this latest controversy is sure to spark renewed debate about accountability and standards in British broadcasting.",
